# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algaeparc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:algaeparc/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:algaeparc/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:algaeparc/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:algaeparc/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:algaeparc/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:algaeparc/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:algaeparc/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:algaeparc/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:algaeparc/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:algaeparc/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:algaeparc/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:algaeparc/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:algaeparc/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:algaeparc/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:algaeparc/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:algaeparc/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:algaeparc/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:algaeparc/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:algaeparc/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:algaeparc/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:algaeparc/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:algaeparc/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:algaeparc/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:algaeparc/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:algaeparc/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:algaeparc/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:algaeparc/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:algaeparc/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:algaeparc/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:algaeparc/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:algaeparc/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:algaeparc/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:algaeparc/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:algaeparc/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:algaeparc/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:algaeparc/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:algaeparc/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:algaeparc/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:algaeparc/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:algaeparc/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:algaeparc/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:algaeparc/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:algaeparc/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:algaeparc/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:algaeparc/algaeparc] Wageningen UR (University & Research centre) has constructed **AlgaePARC** (Algae Production And Research Centre) at the Wageningen Campus.
[src:algaeparc/algaeparc] The goal of AlgaePARC is to fill the gap between fundamental research on algae and full-scale algae production facilities.
[src:algaeparc/algaeparc] This will be done by setting up flexible pilot scale facilities to perform applied research and obtain direct practical experience.
[src:algaeparc/algaeparc] It is a joined initiative of BioProcess Engineering and Food & Biobased Research of the Wageningen University.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The roots of biodiesel as a fuel source can be traced back to when J.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Duffy first conducted transesterification of vegetable oil in 1853, predating Rudolf Diesel's development of the diesel engine.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Diesel's engine, initially designed for mineral oil, successfully ran on peanut oil at the 1900 Paris Exposition.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This landmark event highlighted the potential of vegetable oils as an alternative fuel source.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The interest in using vegetable oils as fuels resurfaced periodically, particularly during resource-constrained periods such as World War II.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] However, challenges such as high viscosity and resultant engine deposits were significant hurdles.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The modern form of biodiesel emerged in the 1930s, when a method was found for transforming vegetable oils for fuel use, laying the groundwork for contemporary biodiesel production.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The physical and chemical properties of biodiesel vary depending on its source and production method.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The trade association National Biodiesel Board defines "biodiesel" as a mono-alkyl ester.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It has been experimented with in railway locomotives and power generators.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Generally characterized by a higher boiling point and flash point than petrodiesel, biodiesel is slightly miscible with water and has distinct lubricating properties.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Its calorific value is approximately 9% lower than that of standard diesel, impacting fuel efficiency.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel production has evolved significantly, with early methods including the direct use of vegetable oils, to more advanced processes like transesterification, which reduces viscosity and improves combustion properties.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Notably, biodiesel production generates glycerol as a by-product, which has its own commercial applications.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel's primary application is in transport.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] There have been efforts to make it a drop-in biofuel, meaning compatible with existing diesel engines and distribution infrastructure.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] However, it is usually blended with petrodiesel, typically to less than 10%, since most engines cannot run on pure biodiesel without modification.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The blend percentage of biodiesel is indicated by a "B" factor.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] B100 represents pure biodiesel, while blends like B20 contain 20% of biodiesel, with the remainder being traditional petrodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] These blends offer a compromise between the environmental benefits of biodiesel and performance characteristics of standard diesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel blends can be used as heating oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The environmental impact of biodiesel is complex and varies based on factors like feedstock type, land use changes, and production methods.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] While it can potentially reduce greenhouse gas emissions compared to fossil fuels, concerns about biodiesel include land use changes, deforestation, and the food vs. fuel debate.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The debate centers on the impact of biodiesel production on food prices and availability, as well as its overall carbon footprint.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Despite these challenges, biodiesel remains a key component in the global strategy to reduce reliance on fossil fuels and mitigate the impacts of climate change.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Blends of biodiesel and conventional hydrocarbon-based diesel are most commonly distributed for use in the retail diesel fuel marketplace.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Blends of 20% biodiesel and lower can be used in diesel equipment with no, or only minor modifications, although certain manufacturers do not extend warranty coverage if equipment is damaged by these blends.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The B6 to B20 blends are covered by the ASTM D7467 specification.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel can also be used in its pure form (B100), but may require certain engine modifications to avoid maintenance and performance problems.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel has a number of standards for its quality including European standard EN 14214, ASTM International D6751, and National Standard of Canada CAN/CGSB-3.524.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] ASTM D6751 (American Society for Testing and Materials) details standards and specifications for biodiesels blended with middle distillate fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This specification standard specifies various test methods to be used in the determination of certain properties for biodiesel blends.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Some of the tests mentioned include flash point and kinematic viscosity.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Transesterification of a vegetable oil was conducted as early as 1853 by Patrick Duffy, four decades before the first diesel engine became functional.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Earlier processes for making lamp oil, were patented (1810, Prague) but not published in peer-reviewed publications.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Rudolf Diesel's prime model, a single 10 ft (3.05 m) iron cylinder with a flywheel at its base, ran on its own power for the first time in Augsburg, Germany, on 10 August 1893 running on nothing but peanut oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In remembrance of this event, 10 August has been declared "International Biodiesel Day".
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It is often reported that Diesel designed his engine to run on peanut oil, but this is not the case.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The engine was constructed for using mineral oil, and was then worked on vegetable oil without any alterations being made.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Despite the widespread use of petroleum-derived diesel fuels, interest in vegetable oils as fuels for internal combustion engines was reported in several countries during the 1920s and 30s and later during World War II.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Belgium, France, Italy, the United Kingdom, Portugal, Germany, Brazil, Argentina, Japan and China were reported to have tested and used vegetable oils as diesel fuels during this time.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Some operational problems were reported due to the high viscosity of vegetable oils compared to petroleum diesel fuel, which results in poor atomization of the fuel in the fuel spray and often leads to deposits and coking of the injectors, combustion chamber and valves.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Attempts to overcome these problems included heating of the vegetable oil, blending it with petroleum-derived diesel fuel or ethanol, pyrolysis and cracking of the oils.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] On 31 August 1937, Georges Chavanne of the University of Brussels (Belgium) was granted a patent for a "Procedure for the transformation of vegetable oils for their uses as fuels" (fr.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] "*Procédé de Transformation d'Huiles Végétales en Vue de Leur Utilisation comme Carburants*") Belgian Patent 422,877.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This patent described the alcoholysis (often referred to as transesterification) of vegetable oils using ethanol (and mentions methanol) in order to separate the fatty acids from the glycerol by replacing the glycerol with short linear alcohols.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This appears to be the first account of the production of what is known as "biodiesel" today.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This is similar (copy) to the patented methods used in the 18th century to make lamp-oil, and may be inspired by some old historical oil lamps, in some places.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] More recently, in 1977, Brazilian scientist Expedito Parente invented and submitted for patent, the first industrial process for the production of biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This process is classified as biodiesel by international norms, conferring a "standardized identity and quality.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] No other proposed biofuel has been validated by the motor industry." As of 2010, Parente's company Tecbio is working with Boeing and NASA to certify bioquerosene (bio-kerosene), another product produced and patented by the Brazilian scientist.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Research into the use of transesterified sunflower oil, and refining it to diesel fuel standards, was initiated in South Africa in 1979.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] By 1983, the process for producing fuel-quality, engine-tested biodiesel was completed and published internationally.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] An Austrian company, Gaskoks, obtained the technology from the South African Agricultural Engineers; the company erected the first biodiesel pilot plant in November 1987, and the first industrial-scale plant in April 1989 (with a capacity of 30,000 tons of rapeseed per annum).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Throughout the 1990s, plants were opened in many European countries, including the Czech Republic, Germany and Sweden.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] France launched local production of biodiesel fuel (referred to as *diester*) from rapeseed oil, which is mixed into regular diesel fuel at a level of 5%, and into the diesel fuel used by some captive fleets (e.g. public transportation) at a level of 30%.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Renault, Peugeot and other manufacturers have certified truck engines for use with up to that level of partial biodiesel; experiments with 50% biodiesel are underway.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] During the same period, nations in other parts of the world also saw local production of biodiesel starting up: by 1998, the Austrian Biofuels Institute had identified 21 countries with commercial biodiesel projects.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] 100% biodiesel is now available at many normal service stations across Europe.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The color of biodiesel ranges from clear to golden to dark brown, depending on the production method and the feedstock used to make the fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This also changes the resulting fuel properties.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In general, biodiesel is slightly miscible with water, has a high boiling point and low vapor pressure.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The flash point of biodiesel can exceed 130 °C (266 °F), significantly higher than that of petroleum diesel which may be as low as 52 °C (126 °F).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel has a density around ~0.88 g/cm3, higher than petrodiesel (~0.85 g/cm3).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The calorific value of biodiesel is about 37.27 MJ/kg.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This is 9% lower than regular Number 2 petrodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Variations in biodiesel energy density is more dependent on the feedstock used than the production process.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Still, these variations are less than for petrodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It has been claimed biodiesel gives better lubricity and more complete combustion thus increasing the engine energy output and partially compensating for the higher energy density of petrodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel Fuels with higher lubricity may increase the usable life of high-pressure fuel injection equipment that relies on the fuel for its lubrication.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Depending on the engine, this might include high pressure injection pumps, pump injectors (also called *unit injectors*) and fuel injectors.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel can be used in pure form (B100) or may be blended with petroleum diesel at any concentration in most injection pump diesel engines.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] New extreme high-pressure (29,000 psi; 200,000 kPa) common rail engines have strict factory limits of B5 or B20, depending on manufacturer.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel has been known to break down deposits of residue in the fuel lines where petrodiesel has been used.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As a result, fuel filters may become clogged with particulates if a quick transition to pure biodiesel is made.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Therefore, it is recommended to change the fuel filters on engines and heaters shortly after first switching to a biodiesel blend.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Since the passage of the Energy Policy Act of 2005, biodiesel use has been increasing in the United States.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In the UK, the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation obliges suppliers to include 5% renewable fuel in all transport fuel sold in the UK by 2010.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] For road diesel, this effectively means 5% biodiesel (B5).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2005, Chrysler (then part of DaimlerChrysler) released the Jeep Liberty CRD diesels from the factory into the European market with 5% biodiesel blends, indicating at least partial acceptance of biodiesel as an acceptable diesel fuel additive.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2007, DaimlerChrysler indicated its intention to increase warranty coverage to 20% biodiesel blends if biofuel quality in the United States can be standardized.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The Volkswagen Group has released a statement indicating that several of its vehicles are compatible with B5 and B100 made from rapeseed oil and compatible with the EN 14214 standard.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The use of the specified biodiesel type in its cars will not void any warranty.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Mercedes-Benz does not allow diesel fuels containing greater than 5% biodiesel (B5) due to concerns about "production shortcomings".
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Any damages caused by the use of such non-approved fuels will not be covered by the Mercedes-Benz Limited Warranty.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Starting in 2004, the city of Halifax, Nova Scotia decided to update its bus system to allow the fleet of city buses to run entirely on a fish-oil based biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This caused the city some initial mechanical issues, but after several years of refining, the entire fleet had successfully been converted.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2007, McDonald's of UK announced it would start producing biodiesel from the waste oil byproduct of its restaurants.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This fuel would be used to run its fleet.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] British train operating company Virgin Trains West Coast claimed to have run the UK's first "biodiesel train", when a Class 220 was converted to run on 80% petrodiesel and 20% biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The British Royal Train on 15 September 2007 completed its first ever journey run on 100% biodiesel fuel supplied by Green Fuels Ltd.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Prince Charles and Green Fuels managing director James Hygate were the first passengers on a train fueled entirely by biodiesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Since 2007, the Royal Train has operated successfully on B100 (100% biodiesel).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A government white paper also proposed converting large portions of the UK railways to biodiesel but the proposal was subsequently dropped in favour of further electrification.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Similarly, a state-owned short-line railroad in Eastern Washington ran a test of a 25% biodiesel / 75% petrodiesel blend during the summer of 2008, purchasing fuel from a biodiesel producer sited along the railroad tracks.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The train will be powered by biodiesel made in part from canola grown in agricultural regions through which the short line runs.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Also in 2007, Disneyland began running the park trains on B98 (98% biodiesel).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The program was discontinued in 2008 due to storage issues, but in January 2009, it was announced that the park would then be running all trains on biodiesel manufactured from its own used cooking oils.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This is a change from running the trains on soy-based biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Washington Cog Railway added the first biodiesel locomotive to its all-steam locomotive fleet.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The fleet has climbed up the western slopes of Mount Washington in New Hampshire since 1868 with a peak vertical climb of 37.4 degrees.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2009, the Grand Canyon Railway started running engine 4960 on used cooking oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] On 8 July 2014, the then Indian Railway Minister D.V.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Sadananda Gowda announced in Railway Budget that 5% bio-diesel will be used in Indian Railways' Diesel Engines.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel can also be used as a heating fuel in domestic and commercial boilers, a mix of heating oil and biofuel which is standardized and taxed slightly differently from diesel fuel used for transportation.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Bioheat fuel is a proprietary blend of biodiesel and traditional heating oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Bioheat is a registered trademark of the National Biodiesel Board [NBB] and the National Oilheat Research Alliance [NORA] in the United States, and Columbia Fuels in Canada.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Heating biodiesel is available in various blends.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] ASTM 396 recognizes blends of up to 5 percent biodiesel as equivalent to pure petroleum heating oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Blends of higher levels of up to 20% biofuel are used by many consumers.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Research is underway to determine whether such blends affect performance.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Older furnaces may contain rubber parts that would be affected by biodiesel's solvent properties, but can otherwise burn biodiesel without any conversion required.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Care must be taken, given that varnishes left behind by petrodiesel will be released and can clog pipes—fuel filtering and prompt filter replacement is required.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Another approach is to start using biodiesel as a blend, and decreasing the petroleum proportion over time can allow the varnishes to come off more gradually and be less likely to clog.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Due to biodiesel's strong solvent properties, the furnace is cleaned out and generally becomes more efficient.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A law passed under Massachusetts Governor Deval Patrick requires all home heating diesel in that state to be 2% biofuel by July 1, 2010, and 5% biofuel by 2013.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] With 80–90% of oil spill costs invested in shoreline cleanup, there is a search for more efficient and cost-effective methods to extract oil spills from the shorelines.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel has displayed its capacity to significantly dissolve crude oil, depending on the source of the fatty acids.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In a laboratory setting, oiled sediments that simulated polluted shorelines were sprayed with a single coat of biodiesel and exposed to simulated tides.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel is an effective solvent to oil due to its methyl ester component, which considerably lowers the viscosity of the crude oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Additionally, it has a higher buoyancy than crude oil, which later aids in its removal.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As a result, 80% of oil was removed from cobble and fine sand, 50% in coarse sand, and 30% in gravel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Once the oil is liberated from the shoreline, the oil-biodiesel mixture is manually removed from the water surface with skimmers.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Any remaining mixture is easily broken down due to the high biodegradability of biodiesel, and the increased surface area exposure of the mixture.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2001, UC Riverside installed a 6-megawatt backup power system that is entirely fueled by biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Backup diesel-fueled generators allow companies to avoid damaging blackouts of critical operations at the expense of high pollution and emission rates.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] By using B100, these generators were able to essentially eliminate the byproducts that result in smog, ozone, and sulfur emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The use of these generators in residential areas around schools, hospitals, and the general public result in substantial reductions in poisonous carbon monoxide and particulate matter.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The power output of biodiesel depends on its blend, quality, and load conditions under which the fuel is burnt.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The thermal efficiency for example of B100 as compared to B20 will vary due to the differing energy content of the various blends.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Thermal efficiency of a fuel is based in part on fuel characteristics such as: viscosity, specific density, and flash point; these characteristics will change as the blends as well as the quality of biodiesel varies.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The American Society for Testing and Materials has set standards in order to judge the quality of a given fuel sample.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] One study found that the brake thermal efficiency of B40 was superior to traditional petroleum counterpart at higher compression ratios (this higher brake thermal efficiency was recorded at compression ratios of 21:1).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was noted that, as the compression ratios increased, the efficiency of all fuel types – as well as blends being tested – increased; though it was found that a blend of B40 was the most economical at a compression ratio of 21:1 over all other blends.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The study implied that this increase in efficiency was due to fuel density, viscosity, and heating values of the fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Fuel systems on some modern diesel engines were not designed to accommodate biodiesel, while many heavy duty engines are able to run with biodiesel blends up to B20.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Traditional direct injection fuel systems operate at roughly 3,000 psi (21,000 kPa) at the injector tip while the modern common rail fuel system operates upwards of 30,000 psi (210,000 kPa) at the injector tip.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Components are designed to operate at a great temperature range, from below freezing to over 1,000 °F (560 °C).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Diesel fuel is expected to burn efficiently and produce as few emissions as possible.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As emission standards are being introduced to diesel engines the need to control harmful emissions is being designed into the parameters of diesel engine fuel systems.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The traditional inline injection system is more forgiving to poorer quality fuels as opposed to the common rail fuel system.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The higher pressures and tighter tolerances of the common rail system allows for greater control over atomization and injection timing.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This control of atomization as well as combustion allows for greater efficiency of modern diesel engines as well as greater control over emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Components within a diesel fuel system interact with the fuel in a way to ensure efficient operation of the fuel system and so the engine.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] If an out-of-specification fuel is introduced to a system that has specific parameters of operation, then the integrity of the overall fuel system may be compromised.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Some of these parameters such as spray pattern and atomization are directly related to injection timing.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] One study found that during atomization, biodiesel and its blends produced droplets greater in diameter than the droplets produced by traditional petrodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The smaller droplets were attributed to the lower viscosity and surface tension of traditional diesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was found that droplets at the periphery of the spray pattern were larger in diameter than the droplets at the center.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This was attributed to the faster pressure drop at the edge of the spray pattern; there was a proportional relationship between the droplet size and the distance from the injector tip.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was found that B100 had the greatest spray penetration, this was attributed to the greater density of B100.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Having a greater droplet size can lead to inefficiencies in the combustion, increased emissions, and decreased horse power.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In another study it was found that there is a short injection delay when injecting biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This injection delay was attributed to the greater viscosity of Biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was noted that the higher viscosity and the greater cetane rating of biodiesel over traditional petrodiesel lead to poor atomization, as well as mixture penetration with air during the ignition delay period.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Another study noted that this ignition delay may aid in a decrease of NO*x* emission.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Emissions are inherent to the combustion of diesel fuels that are regulated by the U.S.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Environmental Protection Agency (E.P.A.).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As these emissions are a byproduct of the combustion process, in order to ensure E.P.A. compliance a fuel system must be capable of controlling the combustion of fuels as well as the mitigation of emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] There are a number of new technologies being phased in to control the production of diesel emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The exhaust gas recirculation system, E.G.R., and the diesel particulate filter, D.P.F., are both designed to mitigate the production of harmful emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The feedstock used to make the biodiesel fuel can significantly alter the resulting exhaust gas and particulate matter emissions, even when blended with commercial diesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A study performed by the Chonbuk National University concluded that a B30 biodiesel blend reduced carbon monoxide emissions by approximately 83% and particulate matter emissions by roughly 33%.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] NO*x* emissions, however, were found to increase without the application of an E.G.R. system.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The study also concluded that, with E.G.R, a B20 biodiesel blend considerably reduced the emissions of the engine.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Additionally, analysis by the California Air Resources Board found that biodiesel had the lowest carbon emissions of the fuels tested, those being ultra-low-sulfur diesel, gasoline, corn-based ethanol, compressed natural gas, and five types of biodiesel from varying feedstocks.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Their conclusions also showed great variance in carbon emissions of biodiesel based on the feedstock used.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Of soy, tallow, canola, corn, and used cooking oil, soy showed the highest carbon emissions, while used cooking oil produced the lowest.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This may cause the filter to clog and interfere with the regeneration process.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In a study on the impact of E.G.R. rates with blends of jathropa biodiesel it was shown that there was a decrease in fuel efficiency and torque output due to the use of biodiesel on a diesel engine designed with an E.G.R. system.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was found that CO and CO2 emissions increased with an increase in exhaust gas recirculation but NO*x* levels decreased.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The opacity level of the jathropa blends was in an acceptable range, where traditional diesel was out of acceptable standards.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was shown that a decrease in Nox emissions could be obtained with an E.G.R. system.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This study showed an advantage over traditional diesel within a certain operating range of the E.G.R. system.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As of 2017, blended biodiesel fuels (especially B5, B8, and B20) are regularly used in many heavy-duty vehicles, especially transit buses in US cities.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Characterization of exhaust emissions showed significant emission reductions compared to regular diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Biodiesel is commonly produced by the transesterification of the vegetable oil or animal fat feedstock, and other non-edible raw materials such as frying oil, etc.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] There are several methods for carrying out this transesterification reaction including the common batch process, heterogeneous catalysts, supercritical processes, ultrasonic methods, and even microwave methods.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Chemically, transesterified biodiesel comprises a mix of mono-alkyl esters of long chain fatty acids.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Using alcohols of higher molecular weights improves the cold flow properties of the resulting ester, at the cost of a less efficient transesterification reaction.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A lipid transesterification production process is used to convert the base oil to the desired esters.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Any free fatty acids (FFAs) in the base oil are either converted to soap and removed from the process, or they are esterified (yielding more biodiesel) using an acidic catalyst.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] After this processing, unlike straight vegetable oil, biodiesel has combustion properties very similar to those of petroleum diesel, and can replace it in most current uses.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The methanol used in most biodiesel production processes is made using fossil fuel inputs.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] However, there are sources of renewable methanol made using carbon dioxide or biomass as feedstock, making their production processes free of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A by-product of the transesterification process is the production of glycerol.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] For every 1 tonne of biodiesel that is manufactured, 100 kg of glycerol are produced.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Originally, there was a valuable market for the glycerol, which assisted the economics of the process as a whole.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] However, with the increase in global biodiesel production, the market price for this crude glycerol (containing 20% water and catalyst residues) has crashed.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Research is being conducted globally to use this glycerol as a chemical building block (see chemical intermediate under Wikipedia article "Glycerol").
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] One initiative in the UK is The Glycerol Challenge.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Usually this crude glycerol has to be purified, typically by performing vacuum distillation.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The refined glycerol (98%+ purity) can then be utilised directly, or converted into other products.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The following announcements were made in 2007: A joint venture of Ashland Inc. and Cargill announced plans to make propylene glycol in Europe from glycerol and Dow Chemical announced similar plans for North America.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Dow also plans to build a plant in China to make epichlorhydrin from glycerol.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Epichlorohydrin is a raw material for epoxy resins.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Global biodiesel production reached 3.8 million tons in 2005.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Approximately 85% of biodiesel production came from the European Union.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] For the year 2006, the latest for which actual production figures could be obtained, total world biodiesel production was about 5–6 million tonnes, with 4.9 million tonnes processed in Europe (of which 2.7 million tonnes was from Germany) and most of the rest from the US.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2007, biodiesel production capacity was growing rapidly, with an average annual growth rate from 2002 to 2006 of over 40%.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2008 production in Europe alone had risen to 7.8 million tonnes.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The capacity for 2008 in Europe totalled 16 million tonnes.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This compares with a total demand for diesel in the US and Europe of approximately 490 million tonnes (147 billion gallons).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In July 2009, a duty was added to American imported biodiesel in the European Union in order to balance the competition from European, especially German producers.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Total world production of vegetable oil for all purposes in 2005–06 was about 110 million tonnes, with about 34 million tonnes each of palm oil and soybean oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] US biodiesel production in 2011 brought the industry to a new milestone.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Under the EPA Renewable Fuel Standard, targets have been implemented for the biodiesel production plants in order to monitor and document production levels in comparison to total demand.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] According to the year-end data released by the EPA, biodiesel production in 2011 reached more than 1 billion gallons.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This production number far exceeded the 800 million gallon target set by the EPA.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As of 2018, Indonesia is the world's top supplier of palm oil-based biofuel with annual production of 3.5 million tons, and expected to export about 1 million tonnes of biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The projected production for 2020 is nearly 12 billion gallons.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A variety of oils can be used to produce biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Animal fats are a by-product of meat production and cooking.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Although it would not be efficient to raise animals (or catch fish) simply for their fat, use of the by-product adds value to the livestock industry (hogs, cattle, poultry).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Today, multi-feedstock biodiesel facilities are producing high quality animal-fat based biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Currently, a 5-million dollar plant is being built in the US, with the intent of producing 11.4 million litres (3 million gallons) biodiesel from some of the estimated 1 billion kg (2.2 billion pounds) of chicken fat produced annually at the local Tyson poultry plant.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Similarly, some small-scale biodiesel factories use waste fish oil as feedstock.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] An EU-funded project (ENERFISH) suggests that at a Vietnamese plant to produce biodiesel from catfish (basa, also known as pangasius), an output of 13 tons/day of biodiesel can be produced from 81 tons of fish waste (in turn resulting from 130 tons of fish).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This project utilises the biodiesel to fuel a CHP unit in the fish processing plant, mainly to power the fish freezing plant.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Current worldwide production of vegetable oil and animal fat is not sufficient to replace liquid fossil fuel use.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Furthermore, some object to the vast amount of farming and the resulting fertilization, pesticide use, and land use conversion that would be needed to produce the additional vegetable oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The advantages of algae are that it can be grown on non-arable land such as deserts or in marine environments, and the potential oil yields are much higher than from plants.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Feedstock yield efficiency per unit area affects the feasibility of ramping up production to the huge industrial levels required to power a significant percentage of vehicles.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Algae fuel yields have not yet been accurately determined, but DOE is reported as saying that algae yield 30 times more energy per acre than land crops such as soybeans.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Yields of 36 tonnes/hectare are considered practical by Ami Ben-Amotz of the Institute of Oceanography in Haifa, who has been farming Algae commercially for over 20 years.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Jatropha has been cited as a high-yield source of biodiesel but yields are highly dependent on climatic and soil conditions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The estimates at the low end put the yield at about 200 US gal/acre (1.5-2 tonnes per hectare) per crop; in more favorable climates two or more crops per year have been achieved.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It is grown in the Philippines, Mali and India, is drought-resistant, and can share space with other cash crops such as coffee, sugar, fruits and vegetables.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It is well-suited to semi-arid lands and can contribute to slow down desertification, according to its advocates.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Transitioning fully to biofuels could require immense tracts of land if traditional food crops are used (although non food crops can be utilized).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The problem would be especially severe for nations with large economies, since energy consumption scales with economic output.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] For third world countries, biodiesel sources that use marginal land could make more sense; e.g., pongam oiltree nuts grown along roads or jatropha grown along rail lines.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In tropical regions, such as Malaysia and Indonesia, plants that produce palm oil are being planted at a rapid pace to supply growing biodiesel demand in Europe and other markets.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Scientists have shown that the removal of rainforest for palm plantations is not ecologically sound since the expansion of oil palm plantations poses a threat to natural rainforest and biodiversity.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It has been estimated in Germany that palm oil diesel has less than one third of the production costs of rapeseed biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In the US, the production of biodiesel was reported in 2018 to support more than 64,000 jobs.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The growth in biodiesel also helps significantly increase GDP.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In 2011, biodiesel created more than $3 billion in GDP.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] One of the main drivers for adoption of biodiesel is energy security.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] This means that a nation's dependence on oil is reduced, and substituted with use of locally available sources, such as coal, gas, or renewable sources.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Thus a country can benefit from adoption of biofuels, without a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] While the total energy balance is debated, it is clear that the dependence on oil is reduced.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] One example is the energy used to manufacture fertilizers, which could come from a variety of sources other than petroleum.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The US National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) states that energy security is the number one driving force behind the US biofuels programme, and a White House "Energy Security for the 21st Century" paper makes it clear that energy security is a major reason for promoting biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The former EU commission president, Jose Manuel Barroso, speaking at a recent EU biofuels conference, stressed that properly managed biofuels have the potential to reinforce the EU's security of supply through diversification of energy sources.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Many countries around the world are involved in the growing use and production of biofuels, such as biodiesel, as an alternative energy source to fossil fuels and oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] To foster the biofuel industry, governments have implemented legislations and laws as incentives to reduce oil dependency and to increase the use of renewable energies.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Many countries have their own independent policies regarding the taxation and rebate of biodiesel use, import, and production.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] It was required by the Canadian Environmental Protection Act Bill C-33 that by 2010, gasoline contained 5% renewable content and that by 2013, diesel and heating oil contained 2% renewable content.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The EcoENERGY for Biofuels Program subsidized the production of biodiesel, among other biofuels, via an incentive rate of CAN$0.20 per liter from 2008 to 2010.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] A decrease of $0.04 will be applied every year following, until the incentive rate reaches $0.06 in 2016.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Individual provinces also have specific legislative measures in regards to biofuel use and production.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The Volumetric Ethanol Excise Tax Credit (VEETC) was the main source of financial support for biofuels, but was scheduled to expire in 2010.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Through this act, biodiesel production guaranteed a tax credit of US$1 per gallon produced from virgin oils, and $0.50 per gallon made from recycled oils.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Currently soybean oil is being used to produce soybean biodiesel for many commercial purposes such as blending fuel for transportation sectors.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The European Union is the greatest producer of biodiesel, with France and Germany being the top producers.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] To increase the use of biodiesel, there are policies requiring the blending of biodiesel into fuels, including penalties if those rates are not reached.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In France, the goal was to reach 10% integration but plans for that stopped in 2010.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] As an incentive for the European Union countries to continue the production of the biofuel, there are tax rebates for specific quotas of biofuel produced.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] In Germany, the minimum percentage of biodiesel in transport diesel is set at 7% so called "B7".
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The United Kingdom's Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) requires fuel suppliers to blend a percentage of renewable fuels into their supply, with a target of 12.4% by 2032.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The UK also mandates B7 diesel (7% biodiesel) and E10 petrol (10% bioethanol).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Tax incentives and grants, such as the Bus Service Operators' Grant (BSOG), further encourage biodiesel use.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] Malaysia plans to implement its nationwide adoption of the B20 palm oil biofuel programme by the end of 2022.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p01] The mandate to manufacture biofuel with a 20% palm oil component - known as B20 - for the transport sector was first rolled out in January 2020 but faced delays due to movement curbs imposed to contain coronavirus outbreaks.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Up to 40% of corn produced in the United States is used to make ethanol, and worldwide 10% of all grain is turned into biofuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A 50% reduction in grain used for biofuels in the US and Europe would replace all of Ukraine's grain exports.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] In some poor countries the rising price of vegetable oil is causing problems.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Some propose that fuel only be made from non-edible vegetable oils such as camelina, jatropha or seashore mallow which can thrive on marginal agricultural land where many trees and crops will not grow, or would produce only low yields.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Others argue that the problem is more fundamental.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Farmers may switch from producing food crops to producing biofuel crops to make more money, even if the new crops are not edible.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The law of supply and demand predicts that if fewer farmers are producing food the price of food will rise.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] It may take some time, as farmers can take some time to change which things they are growing, but increasing demand for first generation biofuels is likely to result in price increases for many kinds of food.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Some have argued that there are poor farmers and poor countries who are making more money because of the higher price of vegetable oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel from sea algae would not necessarily displace terrestrial land currently used for food production and new algaculture jobs could be created.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] By comparison it should be mentioned that the production of biogas utilizes agricultural waste to generate a biofuel known as biogas, and also produces compost, thereby enhancing agriculture, sustainability and food production.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The surge of interest in biodiesels has highlighted a number of environmental effects associated with its use.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] These potentially include reductions in greenhouse gas emissions, deforestation, pollution and the rate of biodegradation.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] See chapter 2.6 of the EPA report for more detailed information.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, environmental organizations, for example, Rainforest Rescue and Greenpeace, criticize the cultivation of plants used for biodiesel production, e.g., oil palms, soybeans and sugar cane.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The deforestation of rainforests exacerbates climate change and sensitive ecosystems are destroyed to clear land for oil palm, soybean and sugar cane plantations.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Moreover, that biofuels contribute to world hunger, since arable land is no longer used for growing foods.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The Environmental Protection Agency published data in January 2012, showing that biofuels made from palm oil will not count towards the renewable fuels mandate of the United States as they are not climate-friendly.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Environmentalists welcome the conclusion because the growth of oil palm plantations has driven tropical deforestation, for example, in Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Indonesia produces biodiesel primarily from palm oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Since agricultural land is limited, in order to plant monocultures of oil palms, land used for other cultivations or the tropical forest need to be cleared.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A major environmental threat is then the destruction of rainforests in Indonesia.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The environmental impact of biodiesel is diverse and not clearcut.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] An often mentioned incentive for using biodiesel is its capacity to lower greenhouse gas emissions compared to those of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Whether this is true or not depends on many factors.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A general critique against biodiesel is the land use change, which have potential to cause even more emissions than what would be caused by using fossil fuels alone.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Yet this problem would be fixed with algal biofuel which can use land unsuitable for agriculture.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Carbon dioxide is one of the major greenhouse gases.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Although the burning of biodiesel produces carbon dioxide emissions similar to those from ordinary fossil fuels, the plant feedstock used in the production absorbs carbon dioxide from the atmosphere when it grows.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Plants absorb carbon dioxide through a process known as photosynthesis which allows it to store energy from sunlight in the form of sugars and starches.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] After the biomass is converted into biodiesel and burned as fuel the energy and carbon is released again.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Some of that energy can be used to power an engine while the carbon dioxide is released back into the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] When considering the total amount of greenhouse gas emissions it is therefore important to consider the whole production process and what indirect effects such production might cause.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The effect on carbon dioxide emissions is highly dependent on production methods and the type of feedstock used.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Calculating the carbon intensity of biofuels is a complex and inexact process, and is highly dependent on the assumptions made in the calculation.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Other factors can be very significant but are sometimes not considered.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] If land use change is not considered and assuming today's production methods, biodiesel from rapeseed and sunflower oil produce 45%-65% lower greenhouse gas emissions than petrodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, there is ongoing research to improve the efficiency of the production process.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel produced from used cooking oil or other waste fat could reduce CO2 emissions by as much as 85%.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] As long as the feedstock is grown on existing cropland, land use change has little or no effect on greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, there is concern that increased feedstock production directly affects the rate of deforestation.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Such clearcutting cause carbon stored in the forest, soil and peat layers to be released.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The amount of greenhouse gas emissions from deforestation is so large that the benefits from lower emissions (caused by biodiesel use alone) would be negligible for hundreds of years.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biofuel produced from feedstock such as palm oil could therefore cause much higher carbon dioxide emissions than some types of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] In the United States, biodiesel is the only alternative fuel to have successfully completed the Health Effects Testing requirements (Tier I and Tier II) of the Clean Air Act (1990).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel can reduce the direct tailpipe-emission of particulates, small particles of solid combustion products, on vehicles with particulate filters by as much as 20 percent compared with low-sulfur (< 50 ppm) diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Particulate emissions as the result of production are reduced by around 50 percent compared with fossil-sourced diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A University of Idaho study compared biodegradation rates of biodiesel, neat vegetable oils, biodiesel and petroleum diesel blends, and neat 2-D diesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The same study examined soil degradation using 10 000 ppm of biodiesel and petroleum diesel, and found biodiesel degraded at twice the rate of petroleum diesel in soil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] In all cases, it was determined biodiesel also degraded more completely than petroleum diesel, which produced poorly degradable undetermined intermediates.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Toxicity studies for the same project demonstrated no mortalities and few toxic effects on rats and rabbits with up to 5000 mg/kg of biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] As biodiesel becomes more widely used, it is important to consider how consumption affects water quality and aquatic ecosystems.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Research examining the biodegradability of different biodiesel fuels found that all of the biofuels studied (including Neat Rapeseed oil, Neat Soybean oil, and their modified ester products) were "readily biodegradable" compounds, and had a relatively high biodegradation rate in water.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Additionally, the presence of biodiesel can increase the rate of diesel biodegradation via co-metabolism.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] As the ratio of biodiesel is increased in biodiesel/diesel mixtures, the faster the diesel is degraded.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Another study using controlled experimental conditions also showed that fatty acid methyl esters, the primary molecules in biodiesel, degraded much faster than petroleum diesel in sea water.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] When considering the emissions from fossil fuel and biofuel use, research typically focuses on major pollutants such as hydrocarbons.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] It is generally recognized that using biodiesel in place of diesel results in a substantial reduction in regulated gas emissions, but there has been a lack of information in research literature about the non-regulated compounds which also play a role in air pollution.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] One study focused on the emissions of non-criteria carbonyl compounds from the burning of pure diesel and biodiesel blends in heavy-duty diesel engines.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The results found that carbonyl emissions of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, acrolein, acetone, propionaldehyde and butyraldehyde, were higher in biodiesel mixtures than emissions from pure diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel use results in higher carbonyl emissions but lower total hydrocarbon emissions, which may be better as an alternative fuel source.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Other studies have been done which conflict with these results, but comparisons are difficult to make due to various factors that differ between studies (such as types of fuel and engines used).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] In a paper which compared 12 research articles on carbonyl emissions from biodiesel fuel use, it found that 8 of the papers reported increased carbonyl compound emissions while 4 showed the opposite.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] This is evidence that there is still much research required on these compounds.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Lubricity of fuel plays an important role in wear that occurs in an engine.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A diesel engine relies on its fuel to provide lubricity for the metal components that are constantly in contact with each other.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel is a much better lubricant compared with fossil petroleum diesel due to the presence of esters.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Tests have shown that the addition of a small amount of biodiesel to diesel can significantly increase the lubricity of the fuel in short term.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, over a longer period of time (2–4 years), studies show that biodiesel loses its lubricity.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] This could be because of enhanced corrosion over time due to oxidation of the unsaturated molecules or increased water content in biodiesel from moisture absorption.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] One of the main concerns regarding biodiesel is its viscosity.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The viscosity of diesel is 2.5–3.2 cSt at 40 °C and the viscosity of biodiesel made from soybean oil is between 4.2 and 4.6 cSt The viscosity of diesel must be high enough to provide sufficient lubrication for the engine parts but low enough to flow at operational temperature.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] High viscosity can plug the fuel filter and injection system in engines.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Vegetable oil is composed of lipids with long chains of hydrocarbons, to reduce its viscosity the lipids are broken down into smaller molecules of esters.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel has higher brake-specific fuel consumption compared to diesel, which means more biodiesel fuel consumption is required for the same torque.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, B20 biodiesel blend has been found to provide maximum increase in thermal efficiency, lowest brake-specific energy consumption, and lower harmful emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The engine performance depends on the properties of the fuel, as well as on combustion, injector pressure and many other factors.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Since there are various blends of biodiesel, that may account for the contradicting reports as regards engine performance.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The feedstock used to make the biodiesel alters the fuel's properties by changing the average carbon chain length and number of double bonds present in the fatty acid methyl esters.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] When biodiesel is cooled below a certain point, some of the molecules aggregate and form crystals.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The fuel starts to appear cloudy once the crystals become larger than one quarter of the wavelengths of visible light – this is the cloud point (CP).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] As the fuel is cooled further these crystals become larger.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The lowest temperature at which fuel can pass through a 45 micrometre filter is the cold filter plugging point (CFPP).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] As biodiesel is cooled further it will gel and then solidify.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Within Europe, there are differences in the CFPP requirements between countries.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] This is reflected in the different national standards of those countries.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The temperature at which pure (B100) biodiesel starts to gel varies significantly and depends upon the mix of esters and therefore the feedstock oil used to produce the biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] For example, biodiesel produced from low erucic acid varieties of canola seed (RME) starts to gel at approximately −10 °C (14 °F).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel produced from beef tallow and palm oil tends to gel at around 16 °C (61 °F) and 13 °C (55 °F) respectively.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] There are a number of commercially available additives that will significantly lower the pour point and cold filter plugging point of pure biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Winter operation is also possible by blending biodiesel with other fuel oils including #2 low sulfur diesel fuel and #1 diesel / kerosene.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Another approach to facilitate the use of biodiesel in cold conditions is by employing a second fuel tank for biodiesel in addition to the standard diesel fuel tank.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The second fuel tank can be insulated and a heating coil using engine coolant is run through the tank.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The fuel tanks can be switched over when the fuel is sufficiently warm.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A similar method can be used to operate diesel vehicles using straight vegetable oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel may contain small but problematic quantities of water.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Although it is only slightly miscible with water it is hygroscopic.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] One of the reasons biodiesel can absorb water is the persistence of mono and diglycerides left over from an incomplete reaction.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] These molecules can act as an emulsifier, allowing water to mix with the biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] In addition, there may be water that is residual to processing or resulting from storage tank condensation.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Previously, the amount of water contaminating biodiesel has been difficult to measure by taking samples, since water and oil separate.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, it is now possible to measure the water content using water-in-oil sensors.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Water contamination is also a potential problem when using certain chemical catalysts involved in the production process, substantially reducing catalytic efficiency of base (high pH) catalysts such as potassium hydroxide.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] There was research into finding more suitable crops and improving oil yield.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Specially bred mustard varieties can produce reasonably high oil yields and are very useful in crop rotation with cereals, and have the added benefit that the meal leftover after the oil has been pressed out can act as an effective and biodegradable pesticide.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The NFESC, with Santa Barbara-based Biodiesel Industries is working to develop biodiesel technologies for the US navy and military, one of the largest diesel fuel users in the world.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A group of Spanish developers working for a company called Ecofasa announced a new biofuel made from trash.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The fuel is created from general urban waste which is treated by bacteria to produce fatty acids, which can be used to make biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Another approach that does not require the use of chemical for the production involves the use of genetically modified microbes.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] NREL experimented with using algae as a biodiesel source in the "Aquatic Species Program".
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] This oil-rich algae can then be extracted from the system and processed into biodiesel, with the dried remainder further reprocessed to create ethanol.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The production of algae to harvest oil for biodiesel has not yet been undertaken on a commercial scale, but feasibility studies have been conducted to arrive at the above yield estimate.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] In addition to its projected high yield, algaculture — unlike crop-based biofuels — does not entail a decrease in food production, since it requires neither farmland nor fresh water.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Many companies are pursuing algae bio-reactors for various purposes, including scaling up biodiesel production to commercial levels.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Biodiesel lipids could be extracted from wet algae using a simple and economical reaction in ionic liquids.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Pongamia plantations for biodiesel production have a two-fold environmental benefit.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The trees both store carbon and produce fuel oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Pongamia grows on marginal land not fit for food crops and does not require nitrate fertilizers.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The oil producing tree has the highest yield of oil producing plant (approximately 40% by weight of the seed is oil) while growing in malnourished soils with high levels of salt.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] It is becoming a main focus in a number of biodiesel research organizations.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The main advantages of Pongamia are a higher recovery and quality of oil than other crops and no direct competition with food crops.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] However, growth on marginal land can lead to lower oil yields which could cause competition with food crops for better soil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Several groups in various sectors are conducting research on *Jatropha curcas*, a poisonous shrub-like tree that produces seeds considered by many to be a viable source of biodiesel feedstock oil.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Much of this research focuses on improving the overall per acre oil yield of Jatropha through advancements in genetics, soil science, and horticultural practices.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] SG Biofuels, a San Diego-based Jatropha developer, has used molecular breeding and biotechnology to produce elite hybrid seeds of Jatropha that show significant yield improvements over first generation varieties.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] SG Biofuels also claims that additional benefits have arisen from such strains, including improved flowering synchronicity, higher resistance to pests and disease, and increased cold weather tolerance.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Plant Research International, a department of the Wageningen University and Research Centre in the Netherlands, maintains an ongoing Jatropha Evaluation Project (JEP) that examines the feasibility of large scale Jatropha cultivation through field and laboratory experiments.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The Center for Sustainable Energy Farming (CfSEF) is a Los Angeles-based non-profit research organization dedicated to Jatropha research in the areas of plant science, agronomy, and horticulture.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Successful exploration of these disciplines is projected to increase Jatropha farm production yields by 200–300% in the next ten years.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] So-called fats, oils and grease (FOG), recovered from sewage can also be turned into biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A group at the Russian Academy of Sciences in Moscow published a paper in 2008, stating that they had isolated large amounts of lipids from single-celled fungi and turned it into biodiesel in an economically efficient manner.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] The recent discovery of a variant of the fungus *Gliocladium roseum* points toward the production of so-called myco-diesel from cellulose.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] This organism was recently discovered in the rainforests of northern Patagonia and has the unique capability of converting cellulose into medium length hydrocarbons typically found in diesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Researchers at the University of Nevada, Reno, have successfully produced biodiesel from oil derived from used coffee grounds.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Their analysis of the used grounds showed a 10% to 15% oil content (by weight).
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] Once the oil was extracted, it underwent conventional processing into biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] It is estimated that finished biodiesel could be produced for about one US dollar per gallon.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] "It won't solve the world's energy problem," Dr.
[src:algaeparc/biodiesel-p02] A microreactor has been developed to convert biodiesel into hydrogen steam to power fuel cells.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In general, biofuels emit fewer greenhouse gas emissions when burned in an engine and are generally considered carbon-neutral fuels as the carbon emitted has been captured from the atmosphere by the crops used in production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] However, life-cycle assessments of biofuels have shown large emissions associated with the potential land-use change required to produce additional biofuel feedstocks.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The outcomes of lifecycle assessments (LCAs) for biofuels are highly situational and dependent on many factors including the type of feedstock, production routes, data variations, and methodological choices.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Estimates about the climate impact from biofuels vary widely based on the methodology and exact situation examined.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Therefore, the climate change mitigation potential of biofuel varies considerably: in some scenarios biofuel emission levels are comparable to fossil fuels, and in other scenarios the use of biofuel results in negative emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Global demand for biofuels is predicted to increase by 56% over 2022–2027.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] By 2027 worldwide biofuel production is expected to supply 5.4% of the world's fuels for transport including 1% of aviation fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Demand for aviation biofuel is forecast to increase.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] However some policy has been criticised for favoring ground transportation over aviation.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The IEA says that biofuel should particularly be used for applications which are difficult to electrify, such as shipping and aviation.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The two most common types of biofuel are bioethanol and biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The United States is the largest producer of bioethanol, while the EU is the largest producer of biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Meanwhile, Brazil produces and uses large amounts of bioethanol in vehicles, including in some flex-fuel cars exclusively available in Brazil.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The energy content in the global production of bioethanol and biodiesel is 2.2 and 1.8 EJ per year, respectively.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The term *biofuel* is used in different ways.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] One definition is "Biofuels are biobased products, in solid, liquid, or gaseous forms.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Other publications reserve the term biofuel for *liquid* or *gaseous* fuels, used for transportation.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report defines *biofuel* as "A fuel, generally in liquid form, produced from biomass.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biofuels include bioethanol from sugarcane, sugar beet or maize, and biodiesel from canola or soybeans.".
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It goes on to define *biomass* in this context as "organic material excluding the material that is fossilized or embedded in geological formations".
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This means that coal or other fossil fuels is not a form of biomass in this context.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Bioethanol is an alcohol made by fermentation, mostly from carbohydrates produced in sugar or starch crops such as maize, sugarcane, or sweet sorghum.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Cellulosic biomass, derived from non-food sources, such as trees and grasses, is also being developed as a feedstock for ethanol production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Ethanol can be used as a fuel for vehicles in its pure form (E100), but it is usually used as a gasoline additive to increase octane ratings and improve vehicle emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biodiesel is produced from oils or fats using transesterification.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It can be used as a fuel for vehicles in its pure form (B100), but it is usually used as a diesel additive to reduce levels of particulates, carbon monoxide, and hydrocarbons from diesel-powered vehicles.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] To avoid a "food versus fuel" dilemma, second-generation biofuels and third-generation biofuels (also called advanced biofuels or sustainable biofuels or drop-in biofuels) are made from feedstocks which do not directly compete with food or feed crop such as waste products and energy crops.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The feedstock used to make the fuels either grow on arable land but are byproducts of the main crop, or they are grown on marginal land.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Second-generation feedstocks also include straw, bagasse, perennial grasses, jatropha, waste vegetable oil, municipal solid waste and so forth.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biologically produced alcohols, most commonly ethanol, and less commonly propanol and butanol, are produced by the action of microorganisms and enzymes through the fermentation of sugars or starches (easiest to produce) or cellulose (more difficult to produce).
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The IEA estimates that ethanol production used 20% of sugar supplies and 13% of corn supplies in 2021.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Ethanol fuel is the most common biofuel worldwide, particularly in Brazil.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Alcohol fuels are produced by fermentation of sugars derived from wheat, corn, sugar beets, sugar cane, molasses and any sugar or starch from which alcoholic beverages such as whiskey, can be made (such as potato and fruit waste, etc.).
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Production methods used are enzyme digestion (to release sugars from stored starches), fermentation of the sugars, distillation and drying.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The distillation process requires significant energy input to generate heat.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Heat is sometimes generated with unsustainable natural gas fossil fuel, but cellulosic biomass such as bagasse is the most common fuel in Brazil, while pellets, wood chips and also waste heat are more common in Europe.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Corn-to-ethanol and other food stocks has led to the development of cellulosic ethanol.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Ethanol fuel can be combined with gasoline to create a more environmentally friendly fuel though there are more viable substitutions to gasoline such as Butanol.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Methanol is currently produced from natural gas, a non-renewable fossil fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In the future it is hoped to be produced from biomass as biomethanol.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This is technically feasible, but the production is currently being postponed for concerns that the economic viability is still pending.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The methanol economy is an alternative to the hydrogen economy to be contrasted with today's hydrogen production from natural gas.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Butanol (C 4H 9OH) is formed by ABE fermentation (acetone, butanol, ethanol) and experimental modifications of the process show potentially high net energy gains with biobutanol as the only liquid product.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] *Escherichia coli* strains have also been successfully engineered to produce butanol by modifying their amino acid metabolism.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] One drawback to butanol production in *E. coli* remains the high cost of nutrient rich media, however, recent work has demonstrated *E. coli* can produce butanol with minimal nutritional supplementation.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biobutanol is sometimes called biogasoline, which is incorrect as it is chemically different, being an alcohol and not a hydrocarbon like gasoline.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biodiesel is the most common biofuel in Europe.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It is produced from oils or fats using transesterification and is a liquid similar in composition to fossil/mineral diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Chemically, it consists mostly of fatty acid methyl (or ethyl) esters (FAMEs).
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Feedstocks for biodiesel include animal fats, vegetable oils, soy, rapeseed, jatropha, mahua, mustard, flax, sunflower, palm oil, hemp, field pennycress, *Pongamia pinnata* and algae.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Pure biodiesel (B100, also known as "neat" biodiesel) currently reduces emissions with up to 60% compared to diesel Second generation B100.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] As of 2020, researchers at Australia's CSIRO have been studying safflower oil as an engine lubricant, and researchers at Montana State University's Advanced Fuels Center in the US have been studying the oil's performance in a large diesel engine, with results described as a "breakthrough".
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biodiesel can be used in any diesel engine and modified equipment when mixed with mineral diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It can also be used in its pure form (B100) in diesel engines, but some maintenance and performance problems may occur during wintertime utilization, since the fuel becomes somewhat more viscous at lower temperatures, depending on the feedstock used.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Electronically controlled 'common rail' and 'Unit Injector' type systems from the late 1990s onwards can only use biodiesel blended with conventional diesel fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] These engines have finely metered and atomized multiple-stage injection systems that are very sensitive to the viscosity of the fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Many current-generation diesel engines are designed to run on B100 without altering the engine itself, although this depends on the fuel rail design.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Since biodiesel is an effective solvent and cleans residues deposited by mineral diesel, engine filters may need to be replaced more often, as the biofuel dissolves old deposits in the fuel tank and pipes.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It also effectively cleans the engine combustion chamber of carbon deposits, helping to maintain efficiency.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biodiesel is an oxygenated fuel, meaning it contains a reduced amount of carbon and higher hydrogen and oxygen content than fossil diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This improves the combustion of biodiesel and reduces the particulate emissions from unburnt carbon.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] However, using pure biodiesel may increase NOx-emissions Biodiesel is also safe to handle and transport because it is non-toxic and biodegradable, and has a high flash point of about 300 °F (148 °C) compared to petroleum diesel fuel, which has a flash point of 125 °F (52 °C).
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In many European countries, a 5% biodiesel blend is widely used and is available at thousands of gas stations.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In France, biodiesel is incorporated at a rate of 8% in the fuel used by all French diesel vehicles.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Avril Group produces under the brand Diester, a fifth of 11 million tons of biodiesel consumed annually by the European Union.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It is the leading European producer of biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Green diesel can be produced from a combination of biochemical and thermochemical processes.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Conventional green diesel is produced through hydroprocessing biological oil feedstocks, such as vegetable oils and animal fats.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Recently, it is produced using series of thermochemical processes such as pyrolysis and hydroprocessing.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In the thermochemical route, syngas produced from gasification, bio-oil produced from pyrolysis or biocrude produced from hydrothermal liquefaction is upgraded to green diesel using hydroprocessing.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Hydroprocessing is the process of using hydrogen to reform a molecular structure.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] For example, hydrocracking which is a widely used hydroprocessing technique in refineries is used at elevated temperatures and pressure in the presence of a catalyst to break down larger molecules, such as those found in vegetable oils, into shorter hydrocarbon chains used in diesel engines.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Green diesel may also be called renewable diesel, drop-in biodiesel, hydrotreated vegetable oil (HVO fuel) or hydrogen-derived renewable diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Unlike biodiesel, green diesel has exactly the same chemical properties as petroleum-based diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It does not require new engines, pipelines or infrastructure to distribute and use, but has not been produced at a cost that is competitive with petroleum.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Gasoline versions are also being developed.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Green diesel is being developed in Louisiana and Singapore by ConocoPhillips, Neste Oil, Valero, Dynamic Fuels, and Honeywell UOP as well as Preem in Gothenburg, Sweden, creating what is known as Evolution Diesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Straight unmodified edible vegetable oil is generally not used as fuel, but lower-quality oil has been used for this purpose.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Used vegetable oil is increasingly being processed into biodiesel, or (more rarely) cleaned of water and particulates and then used as a fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The IEA estimates that biodiesel production used 17% of global vegetable oil supplies in 2021.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Oils and fats reacted with 10 pounds of a short-chain alcohol (usually methanol) in the presence of a catalyst (usually sodium hydroxide [NaOH] can be hydrogenated to give a diesel substitute.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The resulting product is a straight-chain hydrocarbon with a high cetane number, low in aromatics and sulfur and does not contain oxygen.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Hydrogenated oils can be blended with diesel in all proportions.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] They have several advantages over biodiesel, including good performance at low temperatures, no storage stability problems and no susceptibility to microbial attack.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biogasoline can be produced biologically and thermochemically.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The enzymes converted the sugar into fatty acids and then turned these into hydrocarbons that were chemically and structurally identical to those found in commercial gasoline fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The thermochemical approach of producing biogasoline are similar to those used to produce biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biogasoline may also be called drop-in gasoline or renewable gasoline.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Bioethers (also referred to as fuel ethers or oxygenated fuels) are cost-effective compounds that act as octane rating enhancers.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] "Bioethers are produced by the reaction of reactive iso-olefins, such as iso-butylene, with bioethanol." Bioethers are created from wheat or sugar beets, and also be produced from the waste glycerol that results from the production of biodiesel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] They also enhance engine performance, while significantly reducing engine wear and toxic exhaust emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] By greatly reducing the amount of ground-level ozone emissions, they contribute to improved air quality.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In transportation fuel there are six ether additives: dimethyl ether (DME), diethyl ether (DEE), methyl *tert*-butyl ether (MTBE), ethyl *tert*-butyl ether (ETBE), *tert*-amyl methyl ether (TAME), and *tert*-amyl ethyl ether (TAEE).
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The European Fuel Oxygenates Association identifies MTBE and ETBE as the most commonly used ethers in fuel to replace lead.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Ethers were introduced in Europe in the 1970s to replace the highly toxic compound.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Although Europeans still use bioether additives, the U.S.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Energy Policy Act of 2005 lifted a requirement for reformulated gasoline to include an oxygenate, leading to less MTBE being added to fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Although bioethers are likely to replace ethers produced from petroleum in the UK, it is highly unlikely they will become a fuel in and of itself due to the low energy density.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] An aviation biofuel (also known as bio-jet fuel, sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), or bio-aviation fuel (BAF)) is a biofuel used to power aircraft.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The International Air Transport Association (IATA) considers it a key element in reducing the environmental impact of aviation.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Aviation biofuel is used to decarbonize medium and long-haul air travel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] These types of travel generate the most emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Synthetic paraffinic kerosene (SPK) refers to any non-petroleum-based fuel designed to replace kerosene jet fuel, which is often, but not always, made from biomass.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biofuels are biomass-derived fuels from plants, animals, or waste; depending on which type of biomass is used, they could lower CO2 emissions by 20–98% compared to conventional jet fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The first test flight using blended biofuel was in 2008, and in 2011, blended fuels with 50% biofuels were allowed on commercial flights.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In 2023 SAF production was 600 million liters, representing 0.2% of global jet fuel use.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] By 2024, SAF production was to increase to 1.3 billion liters (1 million tonnes), representing 0.3% of global jet fuel consumption and 11% of global renewable fuel production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This increase came as major US production facilities delayed their ramp-up until 2025, having initially been expected to reach 1.9 billion liters.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Small piston engines can be modified to burn ethanol.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Sustainable biofuels are an alternative to electrofuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Sustainable aviation fuel is certified as being sustainable by a third-party organisation.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] SAF technology faces significant challenges due to feedstock constraints.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The oils and fats known as hydrotreated esters and fatty acids (Hefa), crucial for SAF production, are in limited supply as demand increases.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Although advanced e-fuels technology, which combines waste CO2 with clean hydrogen, presents a promising solution, it is still under development and comes with high costs.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] To overcome these issues, SAF developers are exploring more readily available feedstocks such as woody biomass and agricultural and municipal waste, aiming to produce lower-carbon jet fuel more sustainably and efficiently.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biogas is a mixture composed primarily of methane and carbon dioxide produced by the process of anaerobic digestion of organic material by micro-organisms.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Other trace components of this mixture includes water vapor, hydrogen sulfide, siloxanes, hydrocarbons, ammonia, oxygen, carbon monoxide, and nitrogen.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] It can be produced either from biodegradable waste materials or by the use of energy crops fed into anaerobic digesters to supplement gas yields.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The solid byproduct, digestate, can be used as a biofuel or a fertilizer.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] When CO2 and other impurities are removed from biogas, it is called biomethane.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The CO2 can also be combined with hydrogen in methanation to form more methane.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biogas can be recovered from mechanical biological treatment waste processing systems.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Landfill gas, a less clean form of biogas, is produced in landfills through naturally occurring anaerobic digestion.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] If it escapes into the atmosphere, it acts as a greenhouse gas.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In Sweden, "waste-to-energy" power plants capture methane biogas from garbage and use it to power transport systems.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Farmers can produce biogas from cattle manure via anaerobic digesters.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Syngas, a mixture of carbon monoxide, hydrogen and various hydrocarbons, is produced by partial combustion of biomass (combustion with an amount of oxygen that is not sufficient to convert the biomass completely to carbon dioxide and water).
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Before partial combustion the biomass is dried and sometimes pyrolysed.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Syngas is more efficient than direct combustion of the original biofuel; more of the energy contained in the fuel is extracted.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Syngas may be burned directly in internal combustion engines, turbines or high-temperature fuel cells.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The wood gas generator, a wood-fueled gasification reactor, can be connected to an internal combustion engine.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Syngas can be used to produce methanol, dimethyl ether and hydrogen, or converted via the Fischer–Tropsch process to produce a diesel substitute, or a mixture of alcohols that can be blended into gasoline.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Gasification normally relies on temperatures greater than 700 °C.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Lower-temperature gasification is desirable when co-producing biochar, but results in syngas polluted with tar.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The term "biofuels" is also used for solid fuels that are made from biomass, even though this is less common.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Algae can be produced in ponds or tanks on land, and out at sea.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Algal fuels have high yields, a high ignition point, can be grown with minimal impact on fresh water resources, can be produced using saline water and wastewater, and are biodegradable and relatively harmless to the environment if spilled.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] However, production requires large amounts of energy and fertilizer, the produced fuel degrades faster than other biofuels, and it does not flow well in cold temperatures.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] By 2017, due to economic considerations, most efforts to produce fuel from algae have been abandoned or changed to other applications.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Third and fourth-generation biofuels also include biofuels that are produced by bioengineered organisms i.e. algae and cyanobacteria.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Algae and cyanobacteria will use water, carbon dioxide, and solar energy to produce biofuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This method of biofuel production is still at the research level.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The biofuels that are secreted by the bioengineered organisms are expected to have higher photon-to-fuel conversion efficiency, compared to older generations of biofuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] One of the advantages of this class of biofuels is that the cultivation of the organisms that produce the biofuels does not require the use of arable land.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The disadvantages include the cost of cultivating the biofuel-producing organisms being very high.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Also, current methods of using algae often have worse environmental impacts than using other crops.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Recent research highlights that the transition to sustainable energy is reliant on the widespread adoption of third- and fourth-generation biofuels, which utilize non-food sources such as algae and incorporate advanced processes like artificial photosynthesis.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] These alternatives are essential for climate change mitigation because they significantly reduce the land-use competition and sustainability risks associated with earlier biofuel generations.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Electrofuels and solar fuels may or may not be biofuels, depending on whether they contain biological elements.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Electrofuels are made by storing electrical energy in the chemical bonds of liquids and gases.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The primary targets are butanol, biodiesel, and hydrogen, but include other alcohols and carbon-containing gases such as methane and butane.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] A solar fuel is a synthetic chemical fuel produced from solar energy.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Light is converted to chemical energy, typically by reducing protons to hydrogen, or carbon dioxide to organic compounds.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] A bio-digester is a mechanized toilet that uses decomposition and sedimentation to turn human waste into a renewable fuel called biogas.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Biogas can be made from substances like agricultural waste and sewage.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The bio-digester uses a process called anaerobic digestion to produce biogas.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Anaerobic digestion uses a chemical process to break down organic matter with the use of microorganisms in the absence of oxygen to produce biogas.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The processes involved in anaerobic respiration are hydrolysis, acidogenesis, acetogenesis, and methanogenesis.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Global biofuel production was 81 Mtoe in 2017 which represented an annual increase of about 3% compared to 2010.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In 2017, the US was the largest biofuel producer in the world producing 37 Mtoe, followed by Brazil and South America at 23 Mtoe and Europe (mainly Germany) at 12 Mtoe.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] An assessment from 2017 found that: "Biofuels will never be a major transport fuel as there is just not enough land in the world to grow plants to make biofuel for all vehicles.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In 2021, worldwide biofuel production provided 4.3% of the world's fuels for transport, including a very small amount of aviation biofuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] By 2027, worldwide biofuel production is expected to supply 5.4% of the world's fuels for transport including 1% of aviation fuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The US, Europe, Brazil and Indonesia are driving the majority of biofuel consumption growth.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This demand for biodiesel, renewable diesel and biojet fuel is projected to increase by 44% (21 billion litres) over 2022-2027.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Issues relating to biofuel are social, economic, environmental and technical problems that may arise from biofuel production and use.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Social and economic issues include the "food vs fuel" debate and the need to develop responsible policies and economic instruments to ensure sustainable biofuel production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Farming for biofuels feedstock can be detrimental to the environment if not done sustainably.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Environmental concerns include deforestation, biodiversity loss and soil erosion as a result of land clearing for biofuels agriculture.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] While biofuels can contribute to reduction in global carbon emissions, indirect land use change for biofuel production can have the inverse effect.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Technical issues include possible modifications necessary to run the engine on biofuel, as well as energy balance and efficiency.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The International Resource Panel outlined the wider and interrelated factors that need to be considered when deciding on the relative merits of pursuing one biofuel over another.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The IRP concluded that not all biofuels perform equally in terms of their effect on climate, energy security and ecosystems, and suggested that environmental and social effects need to be assessed throughout the entire life-cycle.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In general, biofuels emit fewer greenhouse gas emissions when burned in an engine and are generally considered carbon-neutral fuels as the carbon they emit has been captured from the atmosphere by the crops used in biofuel production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] They can have greenhouse gas emissions ranging from as low as -127.1 gCO2eq per MJ when carbon capture is incorporated into their production to those exceeding 95 gCO2eq per MJ when land-use change is significant.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Several factors are responsible for the variation in emission numbers of biofuel, such as feedstock and its origin, fuel production technique, system boundary definitions, and energy sources.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] However, many government policies, such as those by the European Union and the UK, require that biofuels have at least 65% greenhouse gas emissions savings (or 70% if it is renewable fuels of non-biological origins) relative to fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Life-cycle assessments of first-generation biofuels have shown large emissions associated with the potential land-use change required to produce additional biofuel feedstocks.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] If no land-use change is involved, first-generation biofuels can—on average—have lower emissions than fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] However, biofuel production can compete with food crop production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Up to 40% of corn produced in the United States is used to make ethanol and worldwide 10% of all grain is turned into biofuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Several studies have shown that reductions in emissions from biofuels are achieved at the expense of other impacts, such as acidification, eutrophication, water footprint and biodiversity loss.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Second-generation biofuels are thought to increase environmental sustainability since the non-food part of plants is being used to produce second-generation biofuels instead of being disposed of.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] But the use of second-generation biofuels increases the competition for lignocellulosic biomass, increasing the cost of these biofuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] In theory, third-generation biofuels, produced from algae, shouldn't harm the environment more than first- or second-generation biofuels due to lower changes in land use and the fact that they do not require pesticide use for production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] When looking at the data however, it has been shown that the environmental cost to produce the infrastructure and energy required for third generation biofuel production, are higher than the benefits provided from the biofuels use.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The European Commission has officially approved a measure to phase out palm oil-based biofuels by 2030.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Unsustainable palm oil agriculture has caused significant environmental and social problems, including deforestation and pollution.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] The production of biofuels can be very energy intensive, which, if generated from non-renewable sources, can heavily mitigate the benefits gained through biofuel use.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] A solution proposed to solve this issue is to supply biofuel production facilities with excess nuclear energy, which can supplement the power provided by fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] This can provide a carbon inexpensive solution to help reduce the environmental impacts of biofuel production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] As farmers worldwide respond to higher crop prices in order to maintain the global food supply-and-demand balance, pristine lands are cleared to replace the food crops that were diverted elsewhere to biofuels' production.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Because natural lands, such as rainforests and grasslands, store carbon in their soil and biomass as plants grow each year, clearance of wilderness for new farms translates to a net increase in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Due to this off-site change in the carbon stock of the soil and the biomass, indirect land use change has consequences in the greenhouse gas (GHG) balance of a biofuel.
[src:algaeparc/biofuel] Other authors have also argued that indirect land use changes produce other significant social and environmental impacts, affecting biodiversity, water quality, food prices and supply, land tenure, worker migration, and community and cultural stability.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Examples of bioengineering research include bacteria engineered to produce chemicals, new medical imaging technology, portable and rapid disease diagnostic devices, prosthetics, biopharmaceuticals, and tissue-engineered organs.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Bioengineering overlaps substantially with biotechnology and the biomedical sciences in a way analogous to how various other forms of engineering and technology relate to various other sciences (such as aerospace engineering and other space technology to kinetics and astrophysics).
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Generally, biological engineers attempt to mimic biological systems to create products or modify and control biological systems.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Working with doctors, clinicians, and researchers, bioengineers use traditional engineering principles and techniques to address biological processes, including ways to replace, augment, sustain, or predict chemical and mechanical processes.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Biological engineering is a science-based discipline founded upon the biological sciences in the same way that chemical engineering, electrical engineering, and mechanical engineering can be based upon chemistry, electricity and magnetism, and classical mechanics, respectively.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] , biological engineering had begun being recognized as a branch of engineering and was a new concept to people.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Post-WWII, it grew more rapidly, and the term "bioengineering" was coined by British scientist and broadcaster Heinz Wolff in 1954 at the National Institute for Medical Research.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Wolff graduated that year and became the Division of Biological Engineering director at Oxford.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] This was the first time Bioengineering was recognized as its own branch at a university.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] The early focus of this discipline was electrical engineering due to the work with medical devices and machinery during this time.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] When engineers and life scientists started working together, they recognized that the engineers did not know enough about the actual biology behind their work.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] To resolve this problem, engineers who wanted to get into biological engineering devoted more time to studying the processes of biology, psychology, and medicine.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Because other engineering disciplines also address living organisms, the term biological engineering can be applied more broadly to include agricultural engineering.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] The first biological engineering program in the United States was started at University of California, San Diego in 1966.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] More recent programs have been launched at MIT and Utah State University.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Many old agricultural engineering departments in universities over the world have re-branded themselves as *agricultural and biological engineering* or *agricultural and biosystems engineering*.
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] The average length of study is three to five years, and the completed degree is signified as a bachelor of engineering (B.S. in engineering).
[src:algaeparc/biological-engineering] Fundamental courses include thermodynamics, biomechanics, biology, genetic engineering, fluid and mechanical dynamics, chemical and enzyme kinetics, electronics, and materials properties.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] The composition of a specific source of biomass depends on whether it is derived from plants, animals, microorganisms, or some mixture of all biological matter.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Biomass may also contain material from non-biological origin, due to contamination from anthropogenic activities.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] The table below summarizes the main types of biomasses and their typical sources.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] The composition of biomass on a chemical level is determined by whether it is plant or animal matter.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Biomass is a form of renewable energy useful as fuel and as a source of some chemical products.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Relative to coal and petroleum however, the energy content of biomass is low.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Compared to traditional fossil fuels, biomass has a high oxygen content.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Its carbon is partially combusted, so to speak.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] One such notable example is the production of bio-ethanol.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] There is a general classification of biomass that is produced or sourced for conversion processes.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Biofuels such as bioethanol and biodiesel, and bioplastics, are typically derived from primary or “first-generation” source energy-dense plants and oils such as rapeseed, sugarcane, or corn.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Their high content of sugars and oils makes them ideal as feedstocks, however, there are drawbacks to their use.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] As well as inflating the price of the chosen crop due to increased demand, arable land that would otherwise be used to grow food for human and animal consumption is rendered unavailable.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Secondary or “second-generation” source biomass encompasses a much wider variety of plant and animal matter.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] It may be derived from a relatively pure source, such as wood chippings or grass, or it may be a less well defined solid waste stream.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] This type of biomass is far more challenging to work with, as it contains a more varied mixture of compounds that cannot be easily converted into useful products.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] Despite this, there continues to be intensive research and industry interest in second-generation biomass conversion processes due to its potential to re-use potentially valuable products and derivative products that would otherwise be wasted by incineration.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] In ecological studies, biomass refers to the total amount of biological organisms that are present in a given environment or ecosystem.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] It may encompass the entirety of biological matter, or a subset of species or individuals.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] It is typically expressed as the total weight of carbon that is contained within the chosen group of organisms.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] A 2017 estimate of the total amount of biomass within the biosphere is approximately 550 gigatons of carbon, with a significant majority of this being terrestrial plants (approx.
[src:algaeparc/biomass] To calculate that, remote sensing techniques such as the Normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI), is commonly used to estimate biomass over large scales.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:algaeparc/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] A **fossil fuel** is a flammable carbon compound- or hydrocarbon-containing material formed naturally in the Earth's crust from the buried remains of prehistoric organisms (animals, plants or microplanktons), a process that occurs within geological formations.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Some fossil fuels are further refined into derivatives such as kerosene, gasoline and diesel, or converted into petrochemicals such as polyolefins (plastics), aromatics and synthetic resins.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The origin of fossil fuels is the anaerobic decomposition of buried dead organisms.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The conversion from these organic materials to high-carbon fossil fuels is typically the result of a geological process of millions of years.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Due to the length of time it takes for them to form, fossil fuels are considered non-renewable resources.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In 2023, 77% of primary energy consumption in the world and over 60% of its electricity supply were from fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The large-scale burning of fossil fuels causes serious environmental damage.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Over 70% of the greenhouse gas emissions due to human activity in 2022 was carbon dioxide (CO2) released from burning fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Natural carbon cycle processes on Earth, mostly absorption by the ocean, can remove only a small part of this, and terrestrial vegetation loss due to deforestation, land degradation and desertification further compounds this deficiency.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Therefore, there is a net increase of many billion tonnes of atmospheric CO2 per year.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Although methane leaks are significant, the burning of fossil fuels is the main source of greenhouse gas emissions causing global warming and ocean acidification.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Additionally, most air pollution deaths are due to fossil fuel particulates and noxious gases, and it is estimated that this costs over 3% of the global gross domestic product and that fossil fuel phase-out will save millions of lives each year.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Recognition of the climate crisis, pollution and other negative effects caused by fossil fuels has led to a widespread policy transition and activist movement focused on ending their use in favor of renewable and sustainable energy.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Because the fossil-fuel industry is so heavily integrated in the global economy and heavily subsidized, this transition is expected to have significant economic consequences.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Many stakeholders argue that this change needs to be a just transition and create policy that addresses the societal burdens created by the stranded assets of the fossil fuel industry.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] International policy, in the form of United Nations' sustainable development goals for affordable and clean energy and climate action, as well as the Paris Climate Agreement, is designed to facilitate this transition at a global level.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In 2021, the International Energy Agency concluded that no new fossil fuel extraction projects could be opened if the global economy and society wants to avoid the worst effects of climate change and meet international goals for climate change mitigation.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The theory that fossil fuels formed from the fossilized remains of dead plants by exposure to heat and pressure in Earth's crust over millions of years was first introduced by Andreas Libavius "in his 1597 Alchemia [Alchymia]" and later by Mikhail Lomonosov "as early as 1757 and certainly by 1763".
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The first recorded use of the term "fossil fuel" occurs in the work of the German chemist Caspar Neumann, in English translation in 1759.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The *Oxford English Dictionary* notes that, in the phrase "fossil fuel", the adjective "fossil" means "[o]btained by digging; found buried in the earth", which dates to at least 1652, before the English noun "fossil" came to refer primarily to long-dead organisms in the early 18th century.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Aquatic phytoplankton and zooplankton that died and sedimented in large quantities under anoxic conditions millions of years ago began forming petroleum and natural gas as a result of anaerobic decomposition.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Over geological time this organic matter, mixed with mud, became buried under further heavy layers of inorganic sediment.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The resulting high temperature and pressure caused the organic matter to chemically alter, first into a waxy material known as kerogen, which is found in oil shales, and then with more heat into liquid and gaseous hydrocarbons in a process known as catagenesis.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Despite these heat-driven transformations, the energy released in combustion is still photosynthetic in origin.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Terrestrial plants tend to form coal and methane.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Many of the coal fields date to the Carboniferous period of Earth's history.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Terrestrial plants also form type III kerogen, a source of natural gas.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Although fossil fuels are continually formed by natural processes, they are classified as non-renewable resources because they take millions of years to form and known viable reserves are being depleted much faster than new ones are generated.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Fossil fuels have been important to human development because they can be readily burned in the open atmosphere to produce heat.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The use of peat as a domestic fuel predates recorded history.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Coal was burned in some early furnaces for the smelting of metal ore, while semi-solid hydrocarbons from oil seeps were also burned in ancient times, they were mostly used for waterproofing and embalming.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Commercial exploitation of petroleum began in the 19th century.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Natural gas, once flared-off as an unneeded byproduct of petroleum production, is now considered a very valuable resource.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Natural gas deposits are also the main source of helium.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Heavy crude oil, which is much more viscous than conventional crude oil, and oil sands, where bitumen is found mixed with sand and clay, began to become more important as sources of fossil fuel in the early 2000s.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Oil shale and similar materials are sedimentary rocks containing kerogen, a complex mixture of high-molecular weight organic compounds, which yield synthetic crude oil when heated (pyrolyzed).
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] With additional processing, they can be employed instead of other established fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] During the 2010s and 2020s there was disinvestment from exploitation of such resources due to their high carbon cost relative to more easily-processed reserves.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Prior to the latter half of the 18th century, windmills and watermills provided the energy needed for work such as milling flour, sawing wood or pumping water, while burning wood or peat provided domestic heat.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The wide-scale use of fossil fuels, coal at first and petroleum later, in steam engines enabled the Industrial Revolution.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] At the same time, gas lights using natural gas or coal gas were coming into wide use.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The invention of the internal combustion engine and its use in automobiles and trucks greatly increased the demand for gasoline and diesel oil, both made from fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Other forms of transportation, railways and aircraft, also require fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The other major use for fossil fuels is in generating electricity and as feedstock for the petrochemical industry.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Tar, a leftover of petroleum extraction, is used in the construction of roads.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The energy for the Green Revolution was provided by fossil fuels in the form of fertilizers (natural gas), pesticides (oil), and hydrocarbon-fueled irrigation.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The development of synthetic nitrogen fertilizer has significantly supported global population growth; it has been estimated that almost half of the Earth's population are currently fed as a result of synthetic nitrogen fertilizer use.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The burning of fossil fuels has a number of negative externalities – harmful environmental consequences where the effects extend beyond the people using the fuel.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] These effects vary between different fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] All fossil fuels release CO2 when they burn, thus accelerating climate change.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Burning coal, and to a lesser extent oil and its derivatives, contributes to atmospheric particulate matter, smog and acid rain.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Air pollution from fossil fuels in 2018 has been estimated to cost US$2.9 trillion, or 3.3% of the global gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Climate change is largely driven by the release of greenhouse gases like CO2, and the burning of fossil fuels is the main source of these emissions.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In most parts of the world climate change is negatively impacting ecosystems.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] This includes contributing to the extinction of species and reducing people's ability to produce food, thus adding to the problem of world hunger.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Continued rises in global temperatures will lead to further adverse effects on both ecosystems and people; the World Health Organization has said that climate change is the greatest threat to human health in the 21st century.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Combustion of fossil fuels generates sulfuric and nitric acids, which fall to Earth as acid rain, impacting both natural areas and the built environment.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Monuments and sculptures made from marble and limestone are particularly vulnerable, as the acids dissolve calcium carbonate.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Fossil fuels also contain radioactive materials, mainly uranium and thorium, which are released into the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In 2000, about 12,000 tonnes of thorium and 5,000 tonnes of uranium were released worldwide from burning coal.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] It is estimated that during 1982, US coal burning released 155 times as much radioactivity into the atmosphere as the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Burning coal also generates large amounts of bottom ash and fly ash.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] These materials are used in a wide variety of applications (see Fly ash reuse), utilizing, for example, about 40% of the United States production.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In addition to the effects that result from burning, the harvesting, processing, and distribution of fossil fuels also have environmental effects.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Coal mining methods, particularly mountaintop removal and strip mining, have negative environmental impacts, and offshore oil drilling poses a hazard to aquatic organisms.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Fossil fuel wells can contribute to methane release via fugitive gas emissions.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Oil refineries also have negative environmental impacts, including air and water pollution.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Coal is sometimes transported by diesel-powered locomotives, while crude oil is typically transported by tanker ships, requiring the combustion of additional fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] A variety of mitigating efforts have arisen to counter the negative effects of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] This includes a movement to use alternative energy sources, such as renewable energy.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Environmental regulation uses a variety of approaches to limit these emissions; for example, rules against releasing waste products like fly ash into the atmosphere.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The UN secretary general António Guterres declared that "Humanity is waging war on nature.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Nature always strikes back – and it is already doing so with growing force and fury." He also claimed there is still cause for hope, anticipating the US plan to join other large emitters like China and the EU in adopting targets to reach net zero emissions by 2050.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] According to *Vox* in August 2022*,* "Economists have pointed to energy prices as the main reason for high inflation", noting that "energy prices indirectly affect virtually every part of the economy".
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Sectors that raise prices significantly as a result of higher fossil fuel prices include transportation, food, and shipping.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Mark Zandi of *Moody's* says that fossil fuel prices have driven every big episode of inflation since WWII.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The economic impact of the Russian Invasion of Ukraine in 2022 was a major recent example of fossil fuels causing inflation.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Some economists, including Isabel Schnabel, believe that dependence on fossil fuels is the main driver of the 2021–2022 inflation spike.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Gernot Wagner argues that commodities are undesirable energy sources because they are susceptible to volatile price swings that technologies like renewable energy are not.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] He also argues that technologies improve and get relatively cheaper over time.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Coming out of the COVID-19 pandemic, some argued for the possibility of a base effect phenomenon due to cheaper than normal prices, such as for oil, at the onset of the pandemic, followed by above-average prices which exacerbated the perceived inflation.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] While not expected to provide much short-term relief, the Inflation Reduction Act seeks to make the United States less dependent on fossil fuels and their ability to cause inflation in the economy.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Moody's estimates that by 2030, the bill could reduce the typical American household's spending on energy by more than $300 each year, in 2022 dollars.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Environmental pollution from fossil fuels impacts humans because particulates and other air pollution from fossil fuel combustion may cause illness and death when inhaled.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] These health effects include premature death, acute respiratory illness, aggravated asthma, chronic bronchitis and decreased lung function.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The poor, undernourished, very young and very old, and people with preexisting respiratory disease and other ill health are more at risk.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Global air pollution deaths due to fossil fuels have been estimated at over 8 million people (2018, nearly 1 in 5 deaths worldwide) at 10.2 million (2019), and 5.13 million excess deaths from ambient air pollution from fossil fuel use (2023).
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] While all energy sources inherently have adverse effects, the data show that fossil fuels cause the highest levels of greenhouse gas emissions and are the most dangerous for human health.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In contrast, modern renewable energy sources appear to be safer for human health and cleaner.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] As the data shows, coal, oil, natural gas, and biomass cause higher death rates and higher levels of greenhouse gas emissions than hydropower, nuclear energy, wind, and solar power.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Scientists propose that 1.8 million lives have been saved by replacing fossil fuel sources with nuclear power.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Just transition is a concept that emerged in the 1980s through efforts by U.S. trade unions to protect workers' rights and livelihoods as economies shift to sustainable production, primarily protecting workers affected by environmental regulations.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Since then, it has evolved and gained global recognition, including having a place in the Paris Agreement in 2015.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] A just transition focuses on the connection between energy transition and equitable approaches to decarbonization that support broader development goals.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] A growing number of countries are incorporating just transition strategies to achieve ambitious climate goals, with 38% of 170 countries referring to just transition in their short-term climate plans as of 2022.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Fossil fuel divestment campaigns emerged on college and university campuses in the United States in 2011 with students urging their administrations to turn endowment investments in the fossil fuel industry into investments in clean energy and communities most impacted by climate change.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In 2012, Unity College in Maine became the first institution of higher learning to divest its endowment from fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] While fossil fuel divestment focusses on financial asset management, a related movement, Fossil Free Research, campaigns for universities to stop accepting research funding and sponsorships from fossil fuel companies.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] By 2015, fossil fuel divestment was reportedly the fastest growing divestment movement in history.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] As of July 2023, more than 1593 institutions with assets totalling more than $40.5 trillion in assets worldwide had begun or committed some form of divestment of fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Divesters cite several reasons for their decisions.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] To some, it is a means of aligning investments with core values; to others, it is a tactic for combatting the fossil fuel industry; to others, it is a way to protect portfolios from climate-related financial risk.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Financial research suggests that, in the longer term, fossil fuel divestment has positively impacted investors' returns.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In 2019, Saudi Aramco was listed and it reached a US$2 trillion valuation on its second day of trading, after the world's largest initial public offering.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Fossil fuel subsidies are energy subsidies on fossil fuels.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Under a narrow definition, fossil fuel subsidies totalled around $725 billion (0.6% of global GDP) to $900 billion in 2024.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Under a more expansive definition, they totalled $6.7 trillion (5.8% of GDP).
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Most subsidy is for oil and natural gas.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Subsidies are mainly on consumption, such as a lower sales tax on natural gas for residential heating; or subsidies on production, such as tax breaks on exploration for oil.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Or they may be free or cheap negative externalities; such as air pollution or climate change due to burning gasoline, diesel and jet fuel.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Some fossil fuel subsidies are via electricity generation, such as subsidies for coal-fired power stations.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Eliminating fossil fuel subsidies would reduce the health risks of air pollution, and would greatly reduce global carbon emissions thus helping to limit climate change.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] As of 2021, policy researchers estimate that substantially more money is spent on fossil fuel subsidies than on environmentally harmful agricultural subsidies or environmentally harmful water subsidies.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Despite the G20 countries having pledged to phase-out inefficient fossil fuel subsidies, they continue because of voter demand, or for energy security.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] However the International Institute for Sustainable Development says that, done carefully, phasing-out fossil fuel subsidies would increase energy security.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] The fossil fuels lobby includes paid representatives of corporations involved in the fossil fuel industry (oil, gas, coal), as well as related industries like chemicals, plastics, aviation and other transportation.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Because of their wealth and the importance of energy, transport and chemical industries to local, national and international economies, these lobbies have the capacity and money to attempt to have outsized influence on governmental policy.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] In particular, the lobbies promote climate change denial and obstruct policy related to environmental protection, environmental health and climate action.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] For example, after climate change became a public topic, the fossil fuel lobby began a massive public relations campaign to undermine public understanding of climate change and block meaningful policy action.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Lobbies are active in most fossil-fuel intensive economies with democratic governance, with reporting on the lobbies most prominent in Canada, Australia, the United States and Europe; however, the lobbies are present in many parts of the world.
[src:algaeparc/fossil-fuels] Big Oil companies such as ExxonMobil, Shell, BP, TotalEnergies, Chevron Corporation, and ConocoPhillips are among the largest corporations associated with the fossil fuels lobby.
